The issue here is not because you bought the biggest machine you are going to get the best performance. There are multiple criterias to take into account and you have to investigate on your own 

Resource Allocation - VPS providers are often oversell their physical servers meaning they allocate more virtual machines (VMs) than the physical server can handle. This can lead to performance degradation when multiple VMs on the same server compete for resources like CPU, memory, and disk I/O.

Hardware Specifications: The physical server hosting the VPS might not have the advertised hardware specifications. For example, the CPU might be slower or have fewer cores than expected, or the disk might be slower than advertised.

Network Congestion: While internet connection redirection is uncommon, network congestion on the provider's network or between the provider's network and your location can affect performance. This can lead to slower network speeds and higher latency.

Software Configuration: The performance of the VPS can also be impacted by the software configuration, including the operating system, virtualization software, and other software running on the server.

Misconfiguration: Sometimes, misconfigurations or errors in the VPS setup can cause performance issues. This could include incorrect resource allocations, inefficient software configurations, or compatibility issues between different components.
